close_symbols: Relevant header/name macros/constants (MHD_HEADER_KIND, MHD_HTTP_HEADER_UPGRADE, MHD_HTTP_HEADER_CONNECTION, MHD_HTTP_HEADER_SEC_WEBSOCKET_VERSION, MHD_HTTP_HEADER_SEC_WEBSOCKET_KEY, MHD_HTTP_HEADER_SEC_WEBSOCKET_ACCEPT, MHD_HTTP_METHOD_GET, MHD_HTTP_VERSION_1_1, WS_SEC_WEBSOCKET_VERSION, WS_KEY_LEN, WS_UPGRADE_VALUE, MHD_HTTP_SWITCHING_PROTOCOLS)
explanation: To determine whether ahc_cb modifies any of its formal parameters (violating MISRA rule), the analyzer must know which operations in the function could change the pointer variables themselves or cause indirect modification via called routines. For that we need: (1) the concrete types (enum MHD_Result, struct MHD_Connection, struct MHD_Response) so we can reason about parameter and local variable types and pointer/aliasing; (2) prototypes of every callee used in ahc_cb (MHD_lookup_connection_value, MHD_lookup_connection_value_n, is_websocket_request, send_chat_page, send_bad_request, send_upgrade_required, ws_get_accept_value, MHD_create_response_for_upgrade, MHD_add_response_header, MHD_destroy_response, MHD_queue_response) so we can verify whether any of them accept pointers to the function's parameter variables (e.g. take a pointer-to-pointer to con, req_cls, upload_data_size, etc.) or are implemented as macros with side-effects on parameters; and (3) the macros/constants used in conditional logic so the analyzer can trace control flow and confirm which calls/assignments are reached. With these symbols one can confirm that the function only assigns to *req_cls (the pointee) and does not reassign any of the pointer parameters themselves, and that none of the callees are defined to modify the parameter variables by reference.
